{
  "local_port": 49820,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the books to improve English?",
  "response": "There are many excellent books that can help you improve your English, whether you're focusing on grammar, vocabulary, pronunciation, writing, or general language skills. Here are some highly recommended books for different aspects of English learning:\n\n---\n\n### **Grammar and Vocabulary**\n1. **\"English Grammar in Use\" by Raymond Murphy**  \n   - A classic series for learning English grammar, available at different levels (e.g., beginner, intermediate, advanced).  \n2. **\"Oxford Word Skills\" by Ruth Gairns and Stuart Redman**  \n   - A series of books to improve vocabulary, categorized by level.  \n3. **\"The Blue Book of Grammar and Punctuation\" by Jane Straus**  \n   - A clear guide to grammar rules and punctuation in English.  \n4. **\"Vocabulary in Use\" by Michael McCarthy and Felicity O'Dell**  \n   - A series focused on building vocabulary for everyday and academic use.  \n\n---\n\n### **Writing and Speaking**\n5. **\"On Writing Well\" by William Zinsser**  \n   - A guide to improving writing skills, focusing on clarity and simplicity.  \n6. **\"The Elements of Style\" by Strunk and White**  \n   - A concise guide to writing effectively in English.  \n7. **\"Speak English Like an American\" by Amy Gillett**  \n   - A book focused on improving spoken English and idiomatic expressions.  \n\n---\n\n### **Reading and Comprehension**\n8. **Graded Readers (e.g., Penguin Readers, Oxford Bookworms)**  \n   - Simplified versions of classic and modern stories for learners at different levels.  \n9. **\"Short Stories in English\" by Olly Richards**  \n   - A collection of short stories designed for language learners.  \n10. **\"The New York Times Best Sellers\" or Popular Novels**  \n   - Reading novels in English (e.g., Harry Potter, To Kill a Mockingbird) can improve comprehension and vocabulary.  \n\n---\n\n### **Pronunciation**\n11. **\"Ship or Sheep?\" by Ann Baker**  \n   - A book for improving pronunciation and distinguishing between similar sounds.  \n12. **\"English Pronunciation in Use\" by Mark Hancock**  \n   - A series with audio support for practicing pronunciation.  \n\n---\n\n### **General English Improvement**\n13. **\"Practical English Usage\" by Michael Swan**  \n   - A comprehensive guide to English grammar, vocabulary, and usage.  \n14. **\"The English We Speak\" by BBC Learning English**  \n   - A resource for learning idioms, phrases, and everyday English.  \n15. **\"Word Power Made Easy\" by Norman Lewis**  \n   - A book to build vocabulary and improve language skills.  \n\n---\n\n### **Online Resources**  \nIn addition to books, consider using online resources like Duolingo, BBC Learning English, or Grammarly to supplement your learning.\n\nChoose books that match your current level and goals, and practice consistently for the best results!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
